## Coach-Friendly Summary & Checklist

### Key Points

- **External load** = what the athlete *does* (distance, sprints, actions).
- **Internal load** = how the athlete‚Äôs *body responds* (RPE, HR, wellness).
- For small and medium clubs, **internal load is the best first priority**.
- External load is **nice-to-have**, especially if you already have GPS, but not essential to start managing load well.

### Do‚Äôs

- **Do** start with session-RPE and weekly load.
- **Do** add wellness to get a fuller picture of fatigue and readiness.
- **Do** review data weekly and adjust training based on trends.
- **Do** use external load (if available) to check if your sessions match match demands.
- **Do** keep your system simple and sustainable.

### Don‚Äôts

- **Don‚Äôt** copy elite clubs‚Äô tech without their staff or time.
- **Don‚Äôt** rely only on external data and ignore how players feel.
- **Don‚Äôt** collect data you never review.
- **Don‚Äôt** change metrics every month ‚Äì consistency beats complexity.

### ‚ÄúStart This Month‚Äù Checklist

1. Choose your **RPE scale** (0‚Äì10) and educate players.
1. Implement **session-RPE** after every main session and match.
1. Track **weekly load** per player.
1. Add a **5-question wellness check** on key days.
1. Sit down once a week for **15‚Äì20 minutes** to review trends.
1. Make **one clear adjustment** to next week‚Äôs plan based on what you see.
1. If you later add GPS, use it to **enhance**, not replace, your internal monitoring.

**Coach Takeaway:**\
For most small and medium clubs, **getting internal load right will give you 80% of the value for 20% of the cost and effort.**

